      "title": "When any object is always included/excluded",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Different Cases&nbsp;</strong></h3><p><strong>Type 1: Always including / excluding&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Though for finding arrangements in such cases we have direct formulas of permutations, but we will focus on following approach which do not requires any cramming of formula.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Formula</td><td>included</td><td>excluded</td></tr><tr><td>Permutation of $\\text{n}$ different objects</td><td>&nbsp;</td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\text{ taken } \\text{ r } \\text{ at } \\text{ a } \\text{ time } \\text{ of } \\text{ which } \\text{ p } \\text{ are } &nbsp;\\text{ always } \\\\ \\end{array}$</td><td>${{\\text{r}}^{\\text{n}-\\text{p}}~}{{\\text{P}}_{\\text{r}-\\text{p}}}~$</td><td>${{~}^{\\text{n}-\\text{p}}}{{\\text{P}}_{\\text{r}}}$</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Now let us solve an example to illustrate the use of combinations so that we do not require to use the above formulas.</p><p><strong>Q) How many 3 letter words can be formed by letters of the word SOCIETY when&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(a) $\\text{S}$ is always included&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(b) $\\text{S}$ is always excluded?&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>See here we need to make 3 letter words from 8 letters. So before finding the arrangements we need to select 3 letters and we will then arrange those letters.</p><p>(a) Now since S always have to be included, we can say that it has already been selected, and thus we need to select only 2 object/letters from the remaining 7 letters.</p><p>This could be done in ${{~}^{7}}{{\\text{C}}_{2}}$ ways</p><p>and now after finding such 3 letter words we can just arrange these 3 letters, which we can do in 3! ways.</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ Total words $={{~}^{7}}{{\\text{C}}_{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }3$ ! ways</p><p>(b) $\\text{S}$ is now not to be taken while selecting the letters. So effectively there are only 7 letters to choose from. So effectively there are only 7 letters to choose from. So selecting 3 letters from 7 can be done in ${{~}^{7}}{{\\text{C}}_{3}}$ ways and the 3 letters can be arranged in 3! ways.</p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\text{ Total }\\text{ such }\\text{ words }={{}^{7}}{{\\text{C}}_{3}}3\\text{ ! }$</p><p>So, you can see that we required no formula while solving this.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dda2c03b9dcaf1afebfc"
    },
    {
      "title": "When some object always/never occur together",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>When some objects, always occur together/never occur together</strong></h3><p><strong>Q) In how many ways can the letters of the word PENCIL be arranged so that&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(i) $\\mathbf{N}$ is always next to $\\mathbf{E}$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(ii) N &amp; $\\mathbf{E}$ are always together.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p><strong>(a) $\\text{N}$ is always next to $\\text{E}$&nbsp;</strong></p><p>In these types of questions let $\\text{EN}$ be one word as they always have to be together in the same order.</p><p>So now we just need to arrange 5 words, which can be done in 5! ways.</p><p><strong>(b) $\\mathbf{N}\\And \\mathbf{E}$ are always together&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Now this question is almost similar to the previous part with the only difference being that here order of $\\text{N}\\And \\text{E}$ is not fixed.</p><p>So here $\\text{N}$ can be ahead/next to $\\text{E}$ i.e. NE/EN are two options.</p><p>Then total arrangements become where $\\text{EN}$ is considered one word.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p><strong>Q) How many words can be formed from the letters of the words TRIANGLE, where the words begin with $\\mathbf{T}$ and end with $\\mathbf{E}$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Here $\\text{T}\\And \\text{E}$ have to be starting &amp; ending alphabets respectively.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>There are 6 places to be filled in, which can be arranged in 6! ways.</p><p>Ans. = <img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>Now here is a very common error, students leave this question here only, though there are still many more cases to solve. Question did not define the no. of alphabets in the word, so the following cases will also be counted.</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\text{ Case }\\text{ 2 }: &amp; 2\\text{ Letter }\\text{ Word } &amp; \\text{ TE } &amp; =1\\text{ way } \\\\ \\text{ Case }3: &amp; 3\\text{ Letter }\\text{ Word } &amp; \\text{T} \\underset{-}{6}\\text{E} &amp; =6 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>(since the middle word can have 6 words to choose from)</p><p>Case 4: 4 Letter Word $\\text{ T} \\underset{-}{6} \\underset{-}{5}\\text{E }=30$</p><p>Case 5: 5 Letter Word $\\text{ T} \\underset{-}{6} \\underset{-}{5} \\underset{-}{4}\\text{E }=120$</p><p>Case 6: 6 Letter Word $\\text{ T} \\underset{-}{6} \\underset{-}{5} \\underset{-}{4} \\underset{-}{3}\\underset{-}{E}=360$</p><p>Case $7:7$ Letter Word $\\text{ T} \\underset{-}{6} \\underset{-}{5} \\underset{-}{4} \\underset{-}{3} \\underset{-}{2}\\underset{-}{E}=720$</p><p>and we have already covered the case 8 for 8 letter word.</p><p>Adding up all the cases will give us the right answer</p><p>$\\begin{array}{l} {} &amp; =1+6+30+120+360+720+720 \\\\ {} &amp; =1957 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p><strong>Q) You are going to join coaching classes for the preparation of IIT-JEE. You have 6 option in mind. Find the numbers of ways in which&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(a) you can choose any two of them.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(b) You can choose any two of them, one for regular program and one for correspondence program.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>This question is especially covered so as you can differentiate between selection and arrangements.</p><p>(a) This is an easy one, you just need to select any two out of six possible options.</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ Total ways $={{~}^{6}}{{\\text{C}}_{2}}=15$ ways</p><p>(b) Here also you have to choose only 2 but note the difference here. Order matters here.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Regular</p><p>1. Vidyamandir</p><p>2. Zion</p></td><td><p>Correspondence</p><p>Zion</p><p>Vidyamandir</p></td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>are 2 different cases here.</p><p>So, the solution becomes</p><p>= choose any two arrange the two</p><p>$\\downarrow$ $\\downarrow$</p><p>${ }^6 \\mathrm{C}_2$ 2!</p><p>$\\therefore$ total ways $=15 \\quad 2=30$ ways</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dda2c03b9dcaf1afebfd"
    }
